# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bill-bailey-pitcher
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The **1907 major league baseball season** began on April 11, 1907.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 6, with the Chicago Cubs and Detroit Tigers as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the fourth modern World Series on October 8 and ended with Game 5 on October 12.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The Cubs defeated the Tigers, four games to none (with one tie), capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1907-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Chicago White Sox from the 1906 season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Beaneaters renamed as the Boston Doves.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The 1907 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1907-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1907-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1904 season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1907-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 11 with all but the Brooklyn Superbas and Boston Doves playing.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 6.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 8 and October 12.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1907-major-league-baseball-season] 30 tie games (18 in AL, 12 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 8 and ended on October 12 with the Chicago Cubs defeating the Detroit Tigers in the 1907 World Series in five games (one of which being a tie).
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1907-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The **1912 major league baseball season** began on April 11, 1912.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 6, with the New York Giants and Boston Red Sox as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the ninth modern World Series on October 8 and ended with Game 8 on October 16.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The Red Sox defeated the Giants, four games to three (with one tie), capturing their second championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1903.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1912-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Philadelphia Athletics from the 1911 season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1912-major-league-baseball-season] This was the second of four seasons that the Chalmers Award, a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), was given to a player in each league.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1912-major-league-baseball-season] During the season, *Harper's Weekly* conducted a detailed accounting of the expenses of major league clubs, reaching a figure of approximately $175,000 to $200,000.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Rustlers renamed as the Boston Braves.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The 1912 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1912-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day, April 11, featured all sixteen teams, only the second time every team has started their season on the same day (first being two years prior with the 1910 season).
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 8 and October 16.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1912-major-league-baseball-season] 13 tie games (8 in AL, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 8 and ended on October 16 with the Boston Red Sox defeating the New York Giants in the 1912 World Series in seven games.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The 1912 season saw two teams play their last seasons at their respective venues.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The 1912 season saw three teams play in new venues.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1912-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, was renamed to Robison Field by Helene Britton, named after her father and uncle, Frank and Stanley Robison, respectively.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1912-major-league-baseball-season] To accommodate for large crowds, the New York Highlanders would play three home games at the Brush Stadium, home of the New York Giants, on May 30 and a doubleheader on September 2.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The **1914 major league baseball season** began on April 13, 1914, with the first game of the inaugural major league season of the Federal League (having previously existed as a minor league the year before).
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The league declared itself as a "third major league", with its own eight teams, in competition with the established National and American Leagues.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The National League regular season ended on October 6 with the Boston Braves as champions, and the American League regular season concluded the next day with the Philadelphia Athletics as champions.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League season ended on October 10, and saw the Indianapolis Hoosiers winning the Federal League pennant.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason between the National and American Leagues began with Game 1 of the 11th World Series on October 9 and ended with Game 4 on October 13.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Braves swept the Athletics in four games, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Both the National and American Leagues rejected offers by the Federal League for a postseason matchup.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Philadelphia Athletics from the 1913 season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] This was the last of four seasons that the Chalmers Award, a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), was given to a player in each of the established National and American Leagues.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Dodgers renamed as the Brooklyn Robins.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The major-league status of the Federal League was confirmed by the Special Baseball Records Committee (as convened by then-Commissioner of Baseball William Eckert) in 1969.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The 1914 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League, National League, and Federal League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format first put in place for the 1904 season, and which lasted until the 140-game schedule of 1919.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Most teams played more than 154 games, due to tie games (called on account of darkness or weather) that had to be replayed; tie games are excluded from team standings, but the statistics of individual players are included in their season totals.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had its Opening Day on April 13, with a game between Buffalo and Baltimore.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day for the American and National Leagues was on April 14, and featured all 16 teams of those leagues, only the third time those two leagues started their season on the same day (the 1912 season had been the second).
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The National League had its final day of the regular season on October 6, while the American League's final day of the regular season was October 7.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series between AL and NL champions took place between October 9 and October 13.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had the final day of its regular season on October 10.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] 43 tie games (18 in AL, 10 in NL, 15 in FL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 9 and ended on October 13 with the Boston Braves sweeping the Philadelphia Athletics in the 1914 World Series in four games.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The National and American Leagues refused a postseason against the Federal League.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Across two leagues, Dave Davenport tied as a leader in saves at 6 (2 with the Cincinnati Reds of the NL and 4 with the St.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Note: Attendance data for Federal League teams is unavailable.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] They previously played their on August 1 and August 8.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] In all, 29 of their 79 home games were played at Fenway Park.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The team would only play at Fenway through July of the following season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The **1915 major league baseball season** began on April 10, 1915.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League regular season ended on October 3, and saw the Chicago Whales winning the Federal League pennant.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season for the National League and American League ended on October 7, with the Philadelphia Phillies and Boston Red Sox as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 12th World Series on October 8 and ended with Game 5 on October 13.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Red Sox defeated the Phillies, four games to one, capturing their third championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1912.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Boston Braves from the 1914 season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series had again featured the cities of Boston and Philadelphia, though this time with their opposite-league counterparts.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Hoosiers relocated to Newark, New Jersey as the Newark Peppers.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Buffeds, Chicago Federals, and Cleveland Naps renamed as the Buffalo Blues, Chicago Whales, and Cleveland Indians, respectively.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League brought an antitrust lawsuit against the National and American Leagues prior to the 1915 season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The parties eventually reached a settlement and the Federal League disbanded after the season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The 1915 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League, National League, and Federal League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1904 season, and which lasted until the 140-game schedule of 1919.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had its Opening Day on April 10, featuring all eight teams.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day for the American and National Leagues was on April 14, featuring the 16 teams of those two leagues, as had been scheduled the season prior.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had the final day of its regular season on October 3.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season for the National and American Leagues was October 7.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 8 and October 13.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The National League established that player-managers would count against the player limit, so the bench manager would be unable to insert himself in any game during the season without forfeiting the right to carry one of the players on his roster.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The penalty for violating the rule was forfeiture of the game.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] 31 tie games (10 in AL, 13 in NL, 8 in FL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 8 and ended on October 13 with the Boston Red Sox defeating the Philadelphia Phillies in the 1915 World Series in five games.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] With the relocation of the Indianapolis Hoosiers from Indianapolis, Indiana to Newark, New Jersey as the Newark Peppers, they leave Federal League Park and move into Harrison Park.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Braves would play their last game at Fenway Park on July 26, having shared the park with the Boston Red Sox since the middle of 1914, and opened Braves Field on August 18, playing their final 26 of 78 home games and where they would go on to play for 38 seasons through 1952.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Cubs would play their final game at West Side Park on October 3 against the St.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the home of the Chicago Whales (who would fold before the 1916 season), Weeghman Park for the start of the 1916 season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] For games 3 and 4 of the World Series, the Boston Red Sox use the Boston Braves home of Braves Field due to its larger capacity over their home at Fenway Park (40,000 to 27,000).
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1915-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first year in a row where a World Series winning Red Sox used Braves Field.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The **1918 major league baseball season** began on April 15, 1918.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended earlier than originally scheduled, September 2, because of a reduced schedule due to American participation in World War I.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The National League and American League champions were the Chicago Cubs and Boston Red Sox, respectively.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 15th World Series on September 5 and ended with Game 6 on September 11.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The Red Sox defeated the Cubs, four games to two, capturing their fifth championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1916.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1918-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Chicago White Sox from the 1917 season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1918-major-league-baseball-season] American League Opening Day took place on April 15 with four American League teams playing, the Philadelphia Athletics at Boston Red Sox, and the New York Yankees at Washington Senators, while National League Opening Day saw all eight teams play the following day.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1918-major-league-baseball-season] It was the first season since 1906 which saw the two leagues open on different days.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1918-major-league-baseball-season] With World War I ongoing, a "work or fight" mandate was issued by the government, requiring men with non-essential jobs to enlist or take war-related jobs by July 1, or else risk being drafted.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1918-major-league-baseball-season] Baker granted an extension to MLB players through Labor Day, September 2.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1918-major-league-baseball-season] In early August, MLB clubs decided that the regular season would end at that time.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1918-major-league-baseball-season] As a result, the number of regular-season games that each team played varied—123 to 130 for AL teams and 124 to 131 for NL teams, including ties—reduced from their original 154-game schedules.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season would see all teams but the Cleveland Indians and St.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1918-major-league-baseball-season] Later in August, Baker granted a further extension to allow for the World Series to be contested; it began on September 5 and ended on September 11.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1918-major-league-baseball-season] World War I would end two months later, with the Armistice of 11 November 1918.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1918-major-league-baseball-season] 10 tie games (6 in AL, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on September 5 and ended on September 11 with the Boston Red Sox defeating the Chicago Cubs in the 1918 World Series in six games.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1918-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals is gradually referred to as Cardinal Field, after Helene Britton, daughter of the deceased former owner Frank Robison, sells her interest in the team following a deal in March 1917, ending the association between the Cardinals and the Robison family.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1918-major-league-baseball-season] By 1918, Cardinal Field became the name widely used.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The **1921 major league baseball season** began on April 13, 1921.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 2, with the New York Giants and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 18th World Series on October 5 and ended with Game 8 on October 13.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] In the first Subway Series World Series, the Giants defeated the Yankees, five games to three, capturing their second championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1905.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Cleveland Indians from the 1920 season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] 1921 was the first of three straight seasons in which the Yankees would lead the majors in wins.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Babe Ruth broke the single season home run record for the third consecutive season by hitting 59 home runs in 152 games.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Ruth also broke Roger Connor's record for the most home runs all time when he hit his 139th home run on July 18 against Bert Cole.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The record for career strikeouts, previously held by Cy Young was also broken in 1921 by Walter Johnson; Johnson led the league in strikeouts with 143 and ended the season with 2,835 strikeouts.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Young struck out 2,803 during his career.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds set a Major League record for the fewest strikeouts in a season, with only 308.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Future Hall of Famers Kiki Cuyler and Goose Goslin both debuted in September 1921.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The 1921 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 13 with all but the Chicago White Sox and Detroit Tigers playing.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 2.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 5 and October 13.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] 3 tie games (2 in AL, 1 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics had two tie games.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Tigers and Washington Senators had one tie game each.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 5 and ended on October 13 with the New York Giants defeating the New York Yankees in the 1921 World Series in eight games.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] On August 5, the Pittsburgh Pirates 8–5 victory over the Philadelphia Phillies at Forbes Field was the first Major League game to be broadcast on radio.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Harold Arlin calls the game for Pittsburgh station KDKA.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1922-major-league-baseball-season] The **1922 major league baseball season** began on April 12, 1922.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1922-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 1, with the New York Giants and New York Yankees were the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1922-major-league-baseball-season] In a rematch of the previous season, the postseason began with Game 1 of the 19th World Series on October 4 and ended with Game 5 on October 8.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1922-major-league-baseball-season] In the second consecutive iteration of the Subway Series, the Giants defeated the Yankees, four games to zero (with one tie), capturing their third championship in franchise history, and the fourth team to win back-to-back World Series.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1922-major-league-baseball-season] This was the second World Series between the two teams.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1922-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first of eight seasons that "League Awards", a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), were issued.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1922-major-league-baseball-season] Only an American League award was given in 1922.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1922-major-league-baseball-season] The 1922 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1922-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day, April 13, featured all sixteen teams, for the first time since 1917.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1922-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 1.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1922-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 4 and October 8.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1922-major-league-baseball-season] In June, a 1911 rule regarding barnstorming by World Series players was upheld by the National League, though the American League amended the rule to say that no barnstorming could go on past October 31.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1922-major-league-baseball-season] 7 tie games (2 in AL, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/1922-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 4 and ended on October 8 with the New York Giants sweeping the New York Yankees in the 1922 World Series in four games.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/bill-bailey-pitcher] Bailey first pitched in the major leagues in 1907 for the St.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/bill-bailey-pitcher] Louis Browns, and he remained with the team through the 1912 season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/bill-bailey-pitcher] He had one of his best seasons in 1909, when he finished with a 9–10 win-loss record but a 2.44 ERA.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/bill-bailey-pitcher] The next year, Bailey's ERA increased to 3.32 but his win-loss record spiraled to 3-18 for a Browns team that finished with a 47-107-4 record.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/bill-bailey-pitcher] In the inaugural Federal League season of 1914, Bailey struck out more than one batter per inning (131 strikeouts in 1282⁄3 innings, or 9.2 strikeouts per 9 innings), a virtually unheard-of feat in that era.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/bill-bailey-pitcher] In the 1910–19 decade no other pitcher with at least 100 innings pitched even approached that level, with Rube Marquard (7.7 strikeouts per 9 innings in 1911) being second.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/bill-bailey-pitcher] Nonetheless, Bailey had a losing record (7–9) in that season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/bill-bailey-pitcher] In 1915, his second Federal League season, Bailey lost 20 games.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/bill-bailey-pitcher] He went 6–19 with a 4.63 ERA for the Baltimore Terrapins, was traded to the Chicago Whales, and went 3–1 with a 2.16 ERA for Chicago.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/bill-bailey-pitcher] After Bailey's two seasons in the Federal League, he pitched mostly in the minor leagues, with his only major league appearances coming in 1918 (8 games for the Detroit Tigers), 1921 (19 games for the St.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/bill-bailey-pitcher] Louis Cardinals), and 1922 (12 games for the Cardinals).
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/bill-bailey-pitcher] In Bailey's later minor league career, he lost 20 or more games two more times.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/bill-bailey-pitcher] In 1919, he went 24–21 with a 2.67 ERA for the Beaumont Oilers of the Texas League, with whom he played through 1921.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/bill-bailey-pitcher] In 1922, Bailey split his time between the Houston Buffaloes of the Texas League and the Omaha Buffaloes of the Western League.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/bill-bailey-pitcher] He had a combined 17–23 record that year with a 5.20 ERA.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/bill-bailey-pitcher] He last pitched with Omaha in the 1925 season.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/bill-bailey-pitcher] Before Bailey could appear in any games in 1926, he developed intestinal bleeding and was admitted to Baptist Hospital in Houston, where he underwent blood transfusions.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/bill-bailey-pitcher] The Western League held a benefit in his honor.
[src:bill-bailey-pitcher/bill-bailey-pitcher] Bailey seemed to get better for a while, but he died that November while awaiting another transfusion.
